🔴 Critical — New Issues Introduced By the Partial Fix
NEW ISSUE A — syncMux Cannot Safely Wrap sync_mode Writes Inside fsMutex-Held Sections
This is the most dangerous consequence of the partial fix. scheduler.ino:1247, 1257, 1295, 1327, 1337 all write sync_mode while fsMutex is held. The natural fix of wrapping them with portENTER_CRITICAL(&syncMux) is architecturally forbidden here. portENTER_CRITICAL is a spinlock that disables interrupts on the calling core. Holding a FreeRTOS binary mutex (fsMutex) while disabling interrupts prevents the FreeRTOS tick ISR from running — if the GPRS task on Core 0 is simultaneously spinning on portENTER_CRITICAL(&syncMux) waiting for the scheduler to release it, both cores stall indefinitely. The correct fix is to use a local boolean flag inside the fsMutex block, release fsMutex, then apply the syncMux-guarded write outside:
cppbool need_abort = false;
// ... inside fsMutex block ...
need_abort = true;
if (fs_locked) xSemaphoreGive(fsMutex);
// ... outside fsMutex block ...
if (need_abort) {
    portENTER_CRITICAL(&syncMux);
    sync_mode = eHttpStop;
    portEXIT_CRITICAL(&syncMux);
}
NEW ISSUE B — mode_snap Captured Under syncMux But Dispatch Logic Uses Raw sync_mode
gprs.ino:173 correctly captures mode_snap under syncMux. But at gprs.ino:190–194, the actual dispatch if (sync_mode == eSMSStart) reads the raw variable again. Worse, gprs.ino:395 — the critical eHttpBegin gate — reads raw sync_mode with no protection at all. The mode_snap snapshot is currently used only for debug logging and pending-flag clearing, not for any operational dispatch. The entire dispatch block must be converted to use mode_snap consistently throughout.
NEW ISSUE C — mode_snap Pending-Flag Clearing Creates a Silent Command-Drop Race
At gprs.ino:197–200, pending_manual_status/gps/health flags are cleared based on mode_snap, but the outer if() condition that gates this block checks raw sync_mode. If sync_mode changed between the snapshot and the check, the outer if can fail (correctly skipping the SMS/GPS action) while the inner if (mode_snap == eSMSStart) still clears pending_manual_status = false. The result: an operator's manual SMS command is silently discarded with no retry.

